<li id="cite_note-83"><b><a href="#cite_ref-83" title="">^</a></b> Keegan, p.264; Adrian Goldsworthy, <i>The Roman Army at War 100 BC - CE200</i>, Oxford University Press (Oxford 1996) [<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/0198150571" class="internal">ISBN 0-19-815057-1</a>], p. 33; Jo-Ann Shelton, ed., <i>As the Romans Did: A Sourcebook in Roman Social History</i>, Oxford University Press (New York 1998)[<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/019508974X" class="internal">ISBN 0-19-508974-X</a>], pp. 245-249.</li>
<li id="cite_note-84"><b><a href="#cite_ref-84" title="">^</a></b> Goldsworthy, <i>The Roman Army</i>, pp. 22-24, 37-38; Adrian Goldsworthy, <i>Caesar: Life of a Colossus</i>, Yale University Press (New Haven 2006) [ISBN-10: 0300120486, ISBN-13: 978-0-300-12048-6], pp. 384, 410-411, 425-427. Another important factor discussed by Goldsworthy was absence of legionaries on detached duty.</li>
<li id="cite_note-85"><b><a href="#cite_ref-85" title="">^</a></b> Between 343 BC and 241 BC, the Roman army fought every year except for five. Stephen P. Oakley, "The Early Republic," in Harriet I. Flower, editor, <i>The Cambridge Companion to the Roman Republic</i>, Cambridge University Press (Cambridge U.K. 2004) [<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/0521003903" class="internal">ISBN 0-521-00390-3</a>], p. 27.</li>
