<li id="cite_note-94"><b><a href="#cite_ref-94" title="">^</a></b> T. Correy Brennan, "Power and Process Under the Republican 'Constitution'," in Harriet I. Flower, editor, <i>The Cambridge Companion to the Roman Republic</i>, Cambridge University Press (Cambridge U.K. 2004) [<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/0521003903" class="internal">ISBN 0-521-00390-3</a>], Chapter 2; Potter, pp. 66-88; Goldsworthy, <i>The Roman Army</i>, pp. 121-125. Julius Caesar's most talented, effective and reliable subordinate in Gaul, <a href="/wiki/Titus_Labienus" title="Titus Labienus">Titus Labienus</a>, was recommended to him by <a href="/wiki/Pompey" title="Pompey">Pompey</a>. Goldsworthy, <i>The Roman Army</i>, p. 124.</li>
